  "What is the difference between exponential decay and linear decrease?": "",
  "Linear decrease is always faster": "",
  "Exponential decay reaches zero; linear decrease does not": "",
  "Exponential decay decreases by a constant percentage; linear decrease decreases by a constant amount": "",
  "They are the same thing": "",
  "In exponential decay, a fixed percentage is lost each period (the amount lost gets smaller over time). In linear decrease, a fixed amount is subtracted each period. Exponential decay never reaches zero; linear decrease eventually does.": "",
  "What does 'asymptotic behavior' mean in exponential decay?": "",
  "The function stops changing at a certain point": "",
  "The function approaches a limiting value (often zero) but never actually reaches it": "",
  "The function oscillates": "",
  "The function increases without bound": "",
  "Asymptotic behavior means the graph gets infinitely close to a horizontal line (the asymptote) without ever crossing it. For decay toward zero, the quantity is always positive but approaches zero as time goes on.": "",
